We are happy that New Orleans has been spared from the threats of Marco. IHSNO is continuing to monitor Hurricane Laura. The greatest projected impact of the storms locally will be heavy rainfall, moderate winds, and street flooding starting on Wednesday.

Due to the potential impacts, asynchronous instruction will be implemented on Wednesday, August 26, 2020 and Thursday, August 27, 2020. We will be in touch about learning on Friday as this situation unfolds. Please await further instructions from your teachers about your class expectations and deadlines.

Please monitor your IHSNO email and continue to monitor local news outlets for updates and please stay safe.

On this day in history, President Lyndon Baines Johnson signed the Voting Rights Act, guaranteeing African Americans the right to vote. The bill made it illegal to impose restrictions on federal, state and local elections that were designed to deny the vote to Black people.

With the election less than 3 months away, you can register to vote or make sure your voter registration is active by visiting www.vote.org.

post_text:
Update for IHSNO reopening:

Students in need of computers will be able to pick them up during our schedule week beginning Monday, August 10. Each day, a different grade level will be able to pick up their schedules, technology, text books if applicable, uniforms, etc. We will also have a virtual orientation for each grade level, during which you will receive information about the upcoming school year and ask any questions you may have.

Students will report at the below times, according to their last name. Only one student and one adult will be allowed to enter the building to retrieve the necessary materials. Upon entering the building, you will be required to complete a symptom survey and have your temperature checked. Masks are required at all times in the building. If you are experiencing any symptoms of COVID-19, please refrain from coming to the school.

post_text:
IHSNO is concerned about the increasing spread of COVID-19 in New Orleans. IHSNO, in collaboration with the Orleans Parish School Board and the City of New Orleans Health Department, will start the 2020-2021 school year with total distance learning. We are planning for instruction to begin August 14, 2020, for 9th-grade students and all students beginning instruction August 17, 2020.

Information will be shared with families about times to retrieve materials and supplies for the beginning of the school year. This information will be communicated via email, text, and US Mail. We ask that our families ensure IHSNO has the most up-to-date information to ensure communication happens as smoothly as possible.

Our office is open daily from 9:00 am to 3:00 pm to take calls. Questions about the school should be sent to info@ihsnola.org.

Thank you,
Head of School Sean Wilson

post_text:
Dear IHSNO Community,

It is with a heavy heart that I inform you that Mr. Rufus McGee passed away this morning around 11:30 AM. Mr. McGee has been a long time member of the IHSNO community and he has worked tirelessly to ensure that all students receive the best support services available to them. Rufus‚Äô time at IHSNO was one that was filled with many moments of joy, laughter, and seriousness and his consistent care about the disposition of all students.

Mr. McGee will be missed. May Mr. McGee finds rest in the abode of his Creator and the lover of his soul.

More information to follow regarding services and other events memorializing Rev. Dr. Rufus McGee.

Should you need to speak with someone regarding this matter, the schools‚Äô Social Workers Rosara Riley (rosara.ortizriley@ihsnola.org) and Nakeisha Kyle (Nakeisha.kyle@ihsnola.org) will be available and referral to services beginning Monday, June 15, 2020.

Sincerely,
Sean Wilson, sean.wilson@ihsnola.org
CEO/ Head of School

Congratulations to seniors,Genesis McPipe and
Keith Simmons for winning the IHSNO Achievement Award and the Global Citizenship Award.

Each year, IHSNO recognizes our most outstanding students with the IHSNO Achievement Awards and the Global Citizenship Awards. Recipients of these awards have shown academic excellence, upstanding character, and outstanding citizenship throughout their tenure at IHSNO. These students exhibit wholesomeness, leadership, responsibility, diligence, and perseverance.

International High School of New Orleans (IHSNO) announced Derick Mejia as salutatorian with a GPA of 4.4745.

Mejia will attend Wake Forest University, and plans to major in Civil Engineering. He has served as the soccer captain at IHSNO for the past two years and represented the school at ‚ÄúNo Place for Hate‚Äù seminars. He has also been a student mentor for underclass ESL students at IHSNO. Mejia is also a distinguished member of the Principal‚Äôs List for all four years of his high school career.

post_text:
International High School of New Orleans (IHSNO) announced Russell Adelman-Cannon as valedictorian today for its Class of 2020 with a GPA of 4.6444.

Adelman-Cannon plans to attend Loyola University New Orleans this upcoming fall where he will major in biology with a concentration in cell and molecular biology. He has made the Principal‚Äôs List at IHSNO every quarter of his high school career. He was inducted into the National Honor Society, National Beta Club, Rho Kappa (National Social Studies Honor Society) and the Chinese Honor Society. Upon graduating, he will receive a full International Baccalaureate diploma in Chinese and Art.

post_text:
Congratulations to senior Ron Triggs for being selected as a POSSE Scholar from The Posse Foundation. In addition to being a Posse Scholar, Ron also has been accepted to 54 universities and has been award $3 million in scholarship offers.

This is a historical marker for International High School to have a POSSE Scholar. Posse Scholars graduate at a rate of 90 percent. Since 1989, Posse‚Äôs partner colleges have awarded $1.4 billion in scholarships to Scholars. The Posse program recruits from 10 cities across the United States: Atlanta, the Bay Area, Boston, Chicago, D.C., Houston, Los Angeles, Miami, New Orleans, and New York. Fifty-eight partner colleges and universities award Posse Scholarships each year. In 2010, Posse was honored by President Barack Obama with a portion of his $1.4 million Nobel Prize award, one of 10 organizations he chose to recognize. #IHSNOPROUD #POSSESCHOLAR #CLASS2020
